{title: Steal Away}
{subtitle: African American spiritual — Wallace Willis, c. 1862}
{key: F}
{time: 4/4}
{tempo: 64}
{comment: Was used as a coded message for enslaved people planning escape via the Underground Railroad.}

{start_of_chorus}
[F]Steal a[Dm]way, steal a[Gm]way, steal a[C]way to [F]Jesus!
[F]Steal a[Dm]way, steal a[Gm]way [C]home
[F]I ain't got [Dm]long to [Bb]stay [C]here[F]
{end_of_chorus}

{start_of_verse: 1}
[F]My Lord calls [Dm]me, He [Gm]calls me by the [C]thunder
[F]The trumpet [Dm]sounds with[Bb]in my [C]soul
[F]I ain't got [Dm]long to [Bb]stay [C]here[F]
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 2}
[F]Green trees are [Dm]bending, [Gm]poor sinner stands [C]trembling
[F]The trumpet [Dm]sounds with[Bb]in my [C]soul
[F]I ain't got [Dm]long to [Bb]stay [C]here[F]
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 3}
[F]My Lord calls [Dm]me, He [Gm]calls me by the [C]lightning
[F]The trumpet [Dm]sounds with[Bb]in my [C]soul
[F]I ain't got [Dm]long to [Bb]stay [C]here[F]
